title: For Sale:  FN Five-seven IOM
postcontent:
The Five-seven IOM (Individual Officer Model) was the first variant of the Five-seven pistol to be offered to civilian shooters, debuting in 2004. It is now DISCONTINUED. The IOM has a M1913 accessory rail, serrated slide and trigger guard, and fully adjustable rear sight. It also incorporated magazine safety mechanism to prevent the weapon from being fired without a magazine inserted. IOM’s have the rounded trigger guard for gloved finger. The IOM Model use to be only available for agency purchase. Yeah, this is the REAL DEAL. Gun dealers are saying USG IOM. Or IOM with conventional square trigger guard. These are not IOM, but are USG. USG’s are NOT nearly as valuable. This is a REAL IOM model, not a standard USG that sellers MISREPRESENT as IOM's. The differences between the IOM and USG models are: IOM's have only sold about 4700 pieces. IOM's have a rounded trigger guard instead of a square one. IOM's have a smoother grip than the harsh checkered USG grips. 
 Shooting one of these are best described as an AR-15 5.56 round coming out of a pistol with a recoil of a .22 long rifle. These pistols are very accurate too. IOM’s aren't made anymore and have become highly collectible. It comes with one 20 round magazine and a box (not the original box). Unknown round count. Gun is in excellent condition. Bargain priced for rare collection gun. ----$1000 firm-----. Can’t find one on the internet cheaper if at all. Especially local.
Sorry no trades please.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom PSL-54c for an AR-15
postcontent:
I don't really want to trade this weapon, as it has been an ongoing project for the last year, and I have put a lot of time and effort into it, but I want an AR-15, and the way things are going, I will never get one unless I trade for it.  Bear in mind that I am not interested in trading for any less than what I am asking for.  I am not interested in any other guns, cars, dogs, stamp collections, washing machines, workout videos, waffles, or anything that is not an AR-15.  I will also accept $1200 cash firm.

--------------------------------------------
First, let me say what I need in an AR.  
--------------------------------------------
I need an AR-15 from a reliable manufacturer (RRA, S&W, Bushmaster, etc).  Let me know what you've got, and please have a picture.  I would prefer a 20" barrel, 5.56, and some extra mags.

--------------------------------------------
Now, let me get on to what I'm offering.
--------------------------------------------
I have a PSL-54c manufactured by Romarm and imported by Century International Arms in 7.62x54r.  I bought it about two years ago, and I probably have 2000 rounds down the pipe.  I have done a lot of work to this weapon, and had more planned.  There are a couple of things that I have left unfinished to my regret, but it will make a great project for you to finish.  All the serials match except the scopes, but you almost never find matching scopes.

* I replaced the stock (crappy) trigger group with a Tapco G2 with a 4# sharp break.  There is almost no play to this trigger, just a slight squeeze and... SNAP.  
* I have done considerable work to the furnature, including sanding off 2oz of wood for a cleaner look, and completely refinishing it with a beautiful kingwood color.  
* The barrel and receiver have been cryo-treated.
* Replaced the original LPS 4x6 scope with a Russian PSOP 6x24, (both scopes are included), and replaced the red light with blue, which is easier on the eyes.  Something in the light isnt making correct contact with either the original bulb or the new one, so the light is unreliable.  I cleaned most of the contacts, but something still isnt right.
* Mounted a Harris HBRM-S bipod.

Now for the two things I started but never finished.  I started polisihing the bolt carrier, but only made it about half way.  looks great until you take the weapon apart.  And, I was started stripping and bluing the metal, but only finished the receiver cover, but I don't think I like the color, so... I stopped to consider other options.

The feed ramp needs a good polishing.  Occasionally a round fails to feed correctly.  Re-racking fixes the problem 99% of the time, and polishing the ramp should fix it permenantly.

------------------------------------------
So now, what it comes with.
------------------------------------------
8 magazines in various conditions.  All of them work well.  Properly fitting magazines for PSLs are really hit or miss, so good ones can be tough to find.  Four of the magazines have been cleaned up and painted, but two of them have chips and scratches in the paint. (I was in the market for a bake-on finish, but never got around to getting it.  Three of them are beginning to show a little rust, but I have cleaned them up pretty well.  They were the next in line to be refinished.  One magazine has stayed in my cabinet and is in original factory condition.

440 rounds of silver-tipped Russian steel core ammo in the can.
~200 rounds of Yugo light ball.  I didn't actually count, this is just an estimate.

Both scopes and bipod.  Covers for both scopes.
Original sling.
4 pocket mag pouch
Original three piece cleaning rod & cleaning kit, and oil bottle.

Aluminum rolling case in rough condition.  It's seen better days, but it still works.

-------------------------------------------
Conclusion
-------------------------------------------
Wow, I wrote a lot.  Guess it's a good time to wrap it up.  I have a lot of time and money in this gun, and really, only half of my heart is into trading it.  But... it's time for a new toy.

I have a dozen or so other photos.  MSG me with your email address if you would like to see them.

Face-to-Face ONLY in the North Dallas area.  I need a straight trade only, I have no money to throw in no matter how good the deal is.  You must be over 21 and have a valid Texas drivers license, ID, or CHL (prefered)

If you made it this far, thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  WTS SWISS K-31 SPORTERIZED
postcontent:
Cut-down beechwood stocked K-31 in 7.5x55 Swiss. Has been sporterized by previous owner. Recoil pad installed. Straight-pull action. Pull handle back to cock/eject, push forward to lock/load. 6-round detachable box magazine. Very accurate (1.5 MOA), clean, and well maintained. Comes with (non-matching) magazine. You simply cannot get quality like this today, let alone for this price. The Swiss are world-class machinists and just looking at this rifle proves it. The trigger is a smooth, crisp 2-stage trigger. The safety is easy to operate and very secure (actually secures the striker). The sighs are very effective and adjusted correctly. I can provide a target to prove it. 

If you are wondering about availability of ammo… 7.5x55 Swiss was the standard infantry cartridge of Switzerland until the 1990s. They are currently selling it off. It is called GP-11 and available from gunshows and online companies like Sportsmans’ guide. It is excellent quality and non-corrosive—a real bargin. PrviPartizan also loads 7.5x55 Swiss in reloadable brass cases for prices that beat Remington, Winchester, Federal, etc. The bullet diameter is nominally .308, so bullets appropriate for .308 Winchester, 30-30, and .30-’06 also work in the 7.5x55. The reloader will never run out of ammo. With the number of K-31s imported to the US, I am confident ammo will be produced for them for years to come. 

There are also gunsmiths who can covert them to accept .308 Winchester or any of its descendents (.260 Rem, etc.). One can also buy an excellent scope mount from a company called RockSolid Industries or SwissProducts if one is considering turing this into a true hunting rifle. The 7.5x55 is nearly identical to the .308 Winchester. The barrels on K-31s are very high quality, too. I have a semi-inlet fancy Claro Walnut monte-carlo stock for $125 if you want it. Send this thing to E.R. Shaw or some similar outfit and I am sure they could turn it into a world-class hunting rifle. I have $50 Mojo aperture sights if you want them. 

I greatly prefer FTF deals as close to the West side of Cincinnati as possible. My prices are fair. I will trade for things I am looking for: Ithaca M37, S&W 44 Mag revolver, Ruger No. 1 or 3, f, T/C Encore, Finnish Mosin-Nagants, a nice little S&W or Ruger Revolver for my wife's purse.
